{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536265"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:05:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15736"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15736"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.33,0.18,0.34,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95505"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her atrial fibrillation management. She has a history of mitral stenosis, hypertension, chronic kidney disease stage 3, and previous gastrointestinal bleeding two years ago. Her medications include warfarin, perindopril, and pantoprazole. She drinks two glasses of wine most evenings. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her blood pressure is 165/95 mmHg. Recent blood tests show creatinine 210 \u03bcmol/L (45-90), eGFR 32 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90), and liver function tests within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is her HAS-BLED score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["3","4","6","5","2"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe HAS-BLED score is used to assess bleeding risk in patients on anticoagulation. The scoring criteria are:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E: Uncontrolled, systolic blood pressure \u0026gt;160 mmHg (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal renal function\u003C/strong\u003E: Chronic dialysis, renal transplant, or serum creatinine \u0026gt;200 \u03bcmol/L (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal liver function\u003C/strong\u003E: Chronic hepatic disease or biochemical evidence of significant hepatic derangement (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStroke\u003C/strong\u003E: Previous history of stroke (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding\u003C/strong\u003E: Previous bleeding history or predisposition to bleeding (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabile INR\u003C/strong\u003E: Unstable/high INRs or poor time in therapeutic range (\u0026lt;60%) (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElderly\u003C/strong\u003E: Age \u0026gt;65 years (1 point)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrugs or alcohol\u003C/strong\u003E: Concomitant use of drugs that promote bleeding or alcohol excess (\u22658 drinks/week) (1 point each, maximum 2 points). Note that drugs that promote bleeding include antiplatelet agents and NSAIDs only, not warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of \u003Cstrong\u003E5\u003C/strong\u003E is correct in this case: one point each for hypertension (165/95 mmHg), abnormal renal function (creatinine 210 \u03bcmol/L, which is \u0026gt;200 \u03bcmol/L), previous bleeding (gastrointestinal), age \u0026gt;65 years, and alcohol excess (\u22658 drinks/week).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that a high HAS-BLED score (\u22653) indicates increased bleeding risk but is not a contraindication to anticoagulation. Instead, it should prompt identification and correction of modifiable risk factors (such as hypertension, alcohol use, and concurrent medications) while maintaining necessary anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The HAS-BLED score estimates bleeding risk in patients on anticoagulation, with scores \u22653 indicating high risk.","High HAS-BLED scores should prompt correction of modifiable risk factors rather than withholding anticoagulation.","Regular review of modifiable bleeding risk factors is essential in patients on anticoagulation."],"references":["Krishnaswamy S, Galligan D, Davey K. Navigating the risk of stroke and bleeding in atrial fibrillation. Aust J Gen Pract [Internet]. 2025 May;54(5):301\u20135. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2025/may/navigating-the-risk-of-stroke-and-bleeding-in-atri","NPS MedicineWise. Predicting risk with oral anticoagulants \u2013 understanding CHA\u2082DS\u2082-VASc and HAS-BLED [Internet]. Available at: https://www.nps.org.au/news/predicting-risk-with-oral-anticoagulants","Pisters R, Lane DA, Nieuwlaat R, de Vos CB, Crijns HJ, Lip GY. A novel user-friendly score (HAS-BLED) to assess 1-year risk of major bleeding in patients with atrial fibrillation: the Euro Heart Survey. Chest. 2010 Nov;138(5):1093-100. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20299623/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95505"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15736"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95505"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-12T12:37:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-12T12:38:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8427"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"ite